column168: While in transit, (1) box containing (2) 1-gallon bottles of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (UN1789) became crushed as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation. During the off-loading process, the damaged, crushed product began leaking onto the concrete dock floor; a total amount of 1-gallon. A Contractor neutralized the release using Kolorsafe Liquid Acid Neutralizer before absorbing the liquid and containerizing the spill debris into the proper UN-rated shipping container (a vented 55-gallon fiber drum). Additionally, the pallet in which the load was shipped on was also cut-up and containerized for waste disposal. Lastly, the impacted box that the leaking bottles shipped in was neutralized and containerized for waste disposal. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacting by the release.

column168: While in transit, (2) 55DF's containing Sulfuric Acid 1.500 (UN1830) fell over as a result of inadequate preparation for transportation forcing the bung caps to loosen and release 20-gallons of product on the pallet, the trailer floor, and the asphalt beneath the trailer. Contractors neutralized the release using sodium bicarbonate and solidified the liquid with oil dry. The impacted pallet was cut-up and containerized with the rest of the spill debris into (3) 55DF's for waste disposal. No storm drains, water ways, or soil were impacted by the release.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XLU experienced a release of UN1263 Gun Wash from a 5-gallon metal pail. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to a 3’ x 3’ area of the concrete dock floor and pallet. The damaged pail was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. Absorbents were then deployed to clean the release. The impacted absorbents, cleanup debris, and impacted pallet were then placed into two additional 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal XRC experienced a UN2922 Thiocare H101 71% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4-gallons of product released to a 16’ x 18.5’ area of the trailer floor due to a crack in the tote lid. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Spill-X-A was utilized to neutralize the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted rags and PPE into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: Driver alerted Quality Assurance staff that a hazmat package seemed to be giving off a strong smell but there did not appear to be a leak of any kind.  Package was brought to QA for inspection.  No visible damage to the contents inside or to the outer box.  No visible liquid stains on the box indicating any kind of leakage.  Just a very strong smell of the contents. DescribePack: No visible holes or areas of the container appear to be leaking.  Can was tipped in multiple positions to see if there was a leak spot.  Found nothing.  Just a strong smell from the metal can.  Can was place in the box inside of 3 plastic bags.  Padded absorbent was placed inside the bags to act as a  wedge to hold the can in place. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was pulled from the van and dock area and taken to QA for inspection and then placed in the vented hazardous materials area.
